## (4)(c) OFDM in LTE Networks

> Discuss OFDM (Orthogonal Frequency Division Multiplexing) in LTE networks. *(8 marks)*

> *Learn more: [OFDM](/wireless-communications/multiple-access/ofdm)*

---

**What is OFDM?**

OFDM splits a wideband channel into many **narrow subcarriers** that transmit in parallel. Each subcarrier is spaced so they don't interfere (orthogonal).

**Why LTE uses OFDM:**

- **Fights multipath** - narrow subcarriers are less affected by frequency-selective fading
- **Spectral efficiency** - subcarriers can overlap without interference
- **Simple equalization** - each subcarrier sees flat fading
- **Flexible bandwidth** - LTE can use 1.4, 3, 5, 10, 15, or 20 MHz

---

**Cyclic Prefix:**

A copy of the end of each symbol is added to the beginning. This absorbs multipath delay and prevents **inter-symbol interference (ISI)**.

**Downlink vs Uplink:**

- **Downlink:** Uses **OFDMA** (base station can handle high PAPR)
- **Uplink:** Uses **SC-FDMA** (lower PAPR, saves phone battery)

> SC-FDMA is "OFDM with DFT precoding" to reduce peak-to-average power ratio.

